data.content:
verb
/ˌoʊvɚˈsɛl/ -sells; -sold /-ˈsoʊld/ ; -selling
[+ obj] to accept payment or reservations for more rooms, seats, tickets, etc., than you have available
Hotels routinely oversell their rooms, expecting a small percentage of no-shows.
The concert was oversold. [=more tickets were sold than there were seats]
an oversold [=overbooked] flight
to praise (something or someone) too much
Don't oversell yourself in the job interview.
The salesman oversold the features on the new model.
